  "prompt": "What are some examples of solids turning into liquid?",
  "response": "The process of a solid turning into a liquid is known as **melting**. Here are some common examples:\n\n1. **Ice Melting into Water**: Ice (solid) melts at 0\u00b0C (32\u00b0F) and turns into liquid water.  \n2. **Butter Melting**: Solid butter melts into a liquid when heated.  \n3. **Wax Melting**: Candle wax turns into a liquid when exposed to heat.  \n4. **Metal Melting**: Metals like iron, aluminum, or gold melt into a liquid state at high temperatures (e.g., iron melts at 1538\u00b0C).  \n5. **Chocolate Melting**: Solid chocolate melts into a liquid when warmed.  \n6. **Glass Melting**: Solid glass softens and turns into a liquid when heated to very high temperatures.  \n7. **Ice Cream Melting**: Frozen ice cream turns into a liquid when it warms up.  \n8. **Gallium Melting**: Gallium is a metal that melts at around 29.76\u00b0C, turning into a liquid just above room temperature.  \n\nThese examples illustrate the phase transition from solid to liquid caused by the addition of heat.",
